title: For Sale:  Amazing AR-15!  Premium on Accuracy.
postcontent: If you are looking for an accurate AR-15; you just found it.  From the ground up, this rifle has been built with the sole purpose of hitting small targets at long ranges (within reason for its caliber of course).The lower receiver, an Aero Precision Gen. 2, is fitted to an Aero Precision M4 Enhanced upper; and even has the Aero Precision proprietary 15" free float, M-Lok handguard to complement the receivers.The small parts are provided by SI and those include: charging handle (extended latch), forward assist, dust cover, magazine release (with Odin Works enhanced button) and takedown pins.  The ambidexterous short throw selector is by Herra Arms and can be adjusted to work from 45-60 degrees.  The lower parts kit is from Black Rain Ordnance.  The enhanced, slotted trigger guard is from Core-15.  The gun has KNS anti-rotation trigger pins and a Phase 5 EBRV2 Bolt Release.  Now for what sets this apart from the rest of the crowd and drives home those sub moa groups:The stock is a Magpul PRS and is really the only stock worth a dang when it comes to any sort of bench shooting the AR platform; whether that be shooting paper or prairie dogs.The buffer sping is a captured unit from JP and is referred to as the silent buffer spring.  It does not require a detent to hold in place and does not have the "SPROING" sound when cycling.  Its expensive, but its fantastic.  No unecessary flexing up, down, or sideways.The NiB (nickel boron) BCG is from Fail Zero and is rated for full auto.  Its beefy and it promotes a very smooth action.The barrel on this beast is a Wilson Combat Super Sniper .223 Wylde (safely shoot .223 and 5.56) 20" heavy barrel with target crown.  It gets even better with the Wilson Combat adjustable gas block to really dial in the gun and eliminate any trace of recoil from shooting.Last, but maybe most important, the trigger is an Elftmann 3-gun and is adjustable from the mid 2s-4lbs.  It is hands down the best trigger Ive ever used, and Ive used nearly all of them.  You will not be disappointed and you will be very impressed.All that is lacking is a quality optic to get you on target and a colony of praire dogs to mow down.Be the envy of all your friends!I am not looking for any trades and I have no need to sell this so therefore, my price is firm.  I appreciate you looking at it and if I can answer any questions for you, I will gladly.  Thank you.

title: For Sale:  Caspian 1911 in .45 ACP
postcontent: well made, solid, and very reliable Gold Cup Style Caspian Custom full size 1911 with the Caspian integral MagWell. This gun was made by a very good private GunSmith, utilizing all quality parts. The gun was fitted with an (oldschool spot-on) point of aim shooting American Military Colt/Springfield National Match team barrel with the 7791193 number rollmark. I am not a history perfectionist about the 779 NM barrels, but I did research the net like crazy to conclude this as factual. The National Match numbers are shown on the barrel hood in the photos and match the time line of the U.S. Military's 1960's production barrels (sometime around or before 1963). This barrel is hard as the dickens and was RC hardness tested by my GunSmith to prove it. He schooled me on the fascinating history of military barrels and all the great stories behind them. It is configured and fit to shoot fast and on target. This entire 1911 gun has a black duracoat finish. Please stop to look at the great condition and nice looking 45 Gold Cup style 1911. It has a really nice flat top and serrations, Gold Cup Style like the Colt Gold Cup. Please also review the photos to see the Gun's set up and well put together configuration. This very well balanced and professionally fitted combo, sports a full size 5 inch 7791193 Match/Military barrel. The Slide to frame fit was well executed and the gun is filled with good parts. This oldschool Goldcup Style 1911 was outfitted with a real nicely lined up sight combination with a front night sight shown in the photos, that blows away the 10 Ring on targets. I personally test fired it with my local GunSmith Steve Fischer who is a well known GunSmith here in Florida. We were impressed by the old National Match barrel. The rear sight is really nicely lined up to the GoldCup style flat top serrations, making it a nice aesthetic combination. The gun was neatly fit overall and has functioning a Match grade extractor and ejector fitted to it. The hammer is a Chip McKormick Kimber style hammer. The Caspian frame also has a high ride Chip McKormick grip safety fitted to it for a high hold grip so you can line up a nice point of aim shot. This full size metal monster has a great Magwell and Kimber grip set, which provides a positive purchase grip when held. This nice grip it has also helps to blast your target's bullseye away. The frame Magwell and high hold allows fast magazine reloads. It has an ingenious Caspain integral MagWell that really does make a real difference when reloading. As you can see in the photos, it also has a race extended Magazine thumb release for super speedy reloading action. It was coated very nicely, as shown in the pictures and sports some nice and neat Kimber full size magazine-well grips. This gun is a nice treat to take to the range or to your local 1911 gun shooting competition. It has a very low round count, which were fired during the professional test fire my GunSmith performed. I got to shoot a couple magazines worth while he test fired it and I was impressed with the GoldCup style flat top sight plain, and it's sight line up. I am pricing this one lower than my other high end auctions, for what should be an easy and quick sale. It handles more like shooting a 6 inch or 7 inch length barrel 1911, because this gun is solid steel throughout the entire gun. It is filled with quality american parts. I will hate to see this gun go but I need the money. It's another 1911 work of art I photographed with a high quality and high resolution digital camera with 14 megapixels. So what you see is what you get, and is without a doubt quite the shooter for race competition or home defense. This 1911 comes with one Colt magazine that was tuned to the gun by Professional Master GunSmith Steve Fischer, from here in Sunny South Florida. Happy bidding and good luck. Thank you for looking at my auctions. There will be more to come so keep in tune. Before we move on to the rules and payment section of the description... Please allow me to take this time to expand on Fischer's background and facts, as a true Master GunSmith. Steve Fischer is an old buddy of the world famous Wayne Novak, whom I have had the pleasure of meeting. They went to GunSmith School together in the same Class in Colorado over three decades ago, and they graduated from the GunSmith school together. Both men graduating from the same class set out to be partners and legends. They started their careers together working for Armand Swenson. Swenson stole the first idea on Dovetail sights that Wayne Novak firstly invented back then. After a confrontation in regards to this fall out with Swenson... Novak and Fischer quit. Both acclaimed men told me the story along the lines of that in addition to Wayne's idea and first sight design being robbed of him... they both told me the story with a smile, that the Armand parts were out of spec all the time and so hard to work with. They both claim and explained, they "made one gun in the time they could have made 4 if they were using better parts." So they learned a hard lesson and broke free, quitting Swenson's "sweatshop" and workbench. They left the mediocre Armand Swenson outfit and assembly line, to begin their personal rise above the rest of the 1911 world at the time. They began expanding their explosive careers as GunSmiths, and the rest as you know is history. We all know Wayne Novak for his sights and great gunwork. Steve Fischer, Novak's old colleague went on to work for Colt as one of the lead GunSmiths. From there Steve Fischer went onward to open his own successful GunSmith operation, which has stayed open in sunny south Florida for over 3 decades. Steve is also a champ competition shooter, and he still wins Shotgun matches held yearly in Minneapolis to this day. Additionally Steve is so Old-School, he even knows how to shoot from the hip and smokes the competition in whatever style of shooting he chooses. He looks like a battle troll when I go shooting with him. It is a strange unexpected and powerful metamorphosis to see this 71 year old man go from a regular guy into shooting mode. It almost looks like an ora glows around him and he transforms into like some kind of troll or a stalky looking battle dwarf-thing from Lord of the Rings. A real treat to learn from and have as a friend. I have seen the old battle hound at work and it is no joke. Fischer is also the first GunSmith to make a compensated 40 caliber 1911, shown in an old 80's Gun News Gun Magazine back in the year 1980. Steve worked and built up the gun shown in the photos, helping to make it a real master piece in gun mechanics. In addition to the work Fischer did on this gun for me to tune it up, Fischer tuned a nice magazine up to be mated to this speedy and highly responsive race gun... What Fischer did was he timed and tested the innards of the mag in mention, utilizing a CobraMag spring for this gun's Colt Magazine. F.y.i. Whose CobraMag from Trippreasearch dot com, holds the world record of the only 1911 magazine to pass a 55,000 (sick and grueling) round test without failure. That's right, astounding and out of this world! You heard/read it right... 55,000 rounds blasting off without a hiccup, jam, or hitch. Damn that is a nasty record my friends!!! title: For Sale:  Beretta model 21a "jetfire" pocket pistol in .22LR
postcontent: Up for sale, a really nice little Beretta 21A jetfire pocket pistol in the highly desirable .22 LR caliber. It's the perfect and most popular caliber for this type of pistol. .25 has low velocity and is too weak to have any practical use for protection. .32 ACP is powerful enough but way too expensive to use for anything except strictly personal defense. .22LR has enough velocity to penetrate and do the job you want it to, and it's the cheapest most common round on earth so this pistol also doubles as a really fun little plinker or range toy. It's also one of the smallest pistols you can find in Mass      It's a pre 98 pistol and the newer ones are not MA compliant so these are hard to come by in Mass.      The pistol is in very nice shape, the finish is in surprisingly good condition considering that these guns get a little beat up the way people traditionally carry them bouncing around in a pocket. I test fired the gun a week ago and it cycled two mags back to back flawlessly. It comes with the original box, owners manual/ paperwork, and an extra mag.I'm using the proceeds from this sale to find another gun project so I not interested in trades unless it's something particularly rare and interesting. Im all out of FA10 transfers so the transfer will need to be done through an FFL (buyer pays transfer fees)

title: For Sale:  G98/40 JHV HUNGARIAN 8MM MAUSER CLONE RIFLE GERMAN WWII WAR MARKED 1943
postcontent: I purchased this gun at auction as I know it can be a rare bird. It was restocked (ugh!), and also someone changed the front and rear site (double ugh!).The rifle still fires and I've included close ups of all the stamping. Please contact me for questions and/or additional photos. Below is a better explanation of this rifle:The Mannlicher Gew.98/40 German Infantry Rifle was known by the Germans as the Infanterie Gewehre G98/40.These German contract guns were made from 1941 to 1944 by Fémáru Fegyver és Gépgyár, Budapest, (German Ordnance code “jhv”), with some or all of the work possibly subcontracted to Danuvia Gépgyár, Budapest (German Ordnance code “jua”). {Note added by Claven2: During the war, the German’s referred to Fémáru Fegyver és Gépgyár, Budapest as Metallwaren-Waffen und Maschinenfabrik, Budapest (HU). After the war, the arms maker became known commonly as “FEG”. A full list of codes, including jhv, and most WaA's can be referenced in the following Milsurps Knowledge Library entry: "Das Heereswaffenamt" (Detailed Listing of German WaA Markings and Codes)}The Hungarian-made G98/40 is not a mauser, and shares nothing significant with the G98, rather it is a mannlicher-based receiver design patterned after the Hungarian 35M, the only firearm ever purpose-built for the 8x56R cartridge. The G98/40 was contracted as a war-expedient, to exploit the existing 35M tooling. They were issued primarily to the Luftwaffe.Distinguishing features of the G98/40 include:- mannlicher-based receiver design with all steel parts blued;- two-piece bolt with detachable bolt-heads, and bolt handle positonned ahead of the receiver bridge;- chambered in 8x57;- two-piece stock system (similar to that found on the Lee Enfield). Early stocks were walnut, later laminate; and- mauser sling, bayonet and staggered row magazine designs, allowing the use of the K98 sling, bayonet and stripper clips.In 1943, the Hungarian Government, adopted a variation of the G98/40 known as the 43M, which differs slightly in sling and bayonet arrangements, but is otherwise identical to the G98/40.
